body:
With java 9.0.1 this fails with:

```
reference to assertThat is ambiguous
[ERROR] both method assertThat(java.util.function.IntPredicate) in org.assertj.core.api.Assertions
and method <T>assertThat(java.util.function.Predicate<T>) in org.assertj.core.api.Assertions match
```

The workaround is to add a cast the actual argument:

``` java
protected static <T extends Date> T getDate() {
    return (T) new Date();
}

@Test
public void doesCompile() {
    assertThat((Date) getDate()).isEqualTo(getDate());
}
```

the error is explained [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29499847/ambiguous-method-in-java-8-why), basically it is due to the fact that `T` could implement an interface `I` and there is an `assertThat(I)` in `Assertions` making the compiler confused whether to use `assertThat(Date)` or `assertThat(I)`. I personally think the compiler is overzealous in this case :(

@cbxp if you are on 3.8.0 then you can use `AssertionsForClassTypes` as its `assertThat` don't take any interface types which avoids the problem completely. Unfortunately I screwed up 3.9.0 by adding  `assertThat(CompletionStage)` to `AssertionsForClassTypes`.

```java
	protected static <T extends Date> T getDate() {
		return (T) new Date();
	}

	@Test
	public void doesCompile() {
		AssertionsForClassTypes.assertThat(getDate()).isEqualTo(getDate());
	}
```
 so if you need 3.9.0 you have to cast to make it work.

Hard to know if that will work without a reproducible test case but try using https://www.javadoc.io/doc/org.assertj/assertj-core/latest/org/assertj/core/api/AbstractObjectAssert.html#extracting(java.util.function.Function,org.assertj.core.api.InstanceOfAssertFactory) to narrow the extracted type to a String.

ex:
```java
// Create frodo, setting its name, age and Race
 TolkienCharacter frodo = new TolkienCharacter("Frodo", 33, HOBBIT);

 // let's extract and verify Frodo's name:
 assertThat(frodo).extracting(TolkienCharacter::getName, as(InstanceOfAssertFactories.STRING))
                  .startsWith("Fro");
```
